 Here's a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <sstream>
#include <cctype>

int count_word_occurrences(const std::string& filename, const std::string& word) {
    int count = 0;
    std::ifstream file(filename);

    if (!file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Error opening file: " << filename << std::endl;
        return -1;
    }

    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        size_t pos = 0;
        while ((pos = line.find(word, pos))!= std::string::npos) {
            count++;
            pos += word.length(); // Skip over the actual word we just found
            while (isspace(line[pos])) pos++; // Skip over any whitespace that follows the word
        }
    }

    file.close();

    return count;
}

int main() {
    const std::string filename("example.txt");
    const std::string word("the");

    int count = count_word_occurrences(filename, word);

    if (count > 0) {
        std::cout << "The word '" << word << "' appears " << count << " times in the file." << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "The word '" << word << "' does not appear in the file." << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}

This program takes two arguments: the name of the file to read from, and the word to search for. It uses the `std::ifstream` class to open the file and `std::getline` to read each line.

The `count_word_occurrences` function uses the `find` method to search for the word in each line. It skips over the actual word we just found and any whitespace that follows it, so that we only count complete occurrences of the word.

The `main` function calls `count_word_occurrences` and prints the result to the console.

